`crates/ctx-status/src` implements the `ctx-status` binary: a CLI backlog manager that treats `docs/status.json` as the source of truth for prioritized tasks and keeps `docs/STATUS.md` as a generated, never-hand-edited view. Consumers interact through three commands ‚Äî `list`, `add-task`, `delete-task` ‚Äî plus hidden `migrate`/`render` bootstrap/resync commands, all documented verbatim in `contract.rs`'s `CONTRACT` string, which docs generation and a `contracts` battery check both depend on.

The crate is layered top to bottom: `main.rs` wires `fs::StdFs` and handles `--contract`/exit codes; `cli.rs` parses argv and calls `dispatch`; `runner.rs` (and its `runner/` submodule breakdown) is the orchestration layer that loads the JSON store, mutates it, and immediately calls `save()` so the markdown view can never lag; `model.rs` and `render.rs` are the pure core with no I/O or argv coupling. `fs.rs`'s `Fs` trait is the seam separating all of this from the real filesystem, letting tests substitute `FakeFs`.

Two invariants span the whole subtree: (1) task ids are assigned once, via max-existing-id + 1, and legacy zero/missing ids are backfilled ‚Äî `model.rs`, `runner.rs`, and the `runner/` operations all implement this same rule independently, so an id-assignment change must be checked in all three; (2) storage order (insertion/source order) and display order (priority-sorted: high/easy first) are distinct and must not be conflated ‚Äî `list` relies on this split for its backfill correctness. Markdown output is always 4 columns with ids omitted, matching `ctx-brief`'s shared `status_table` format; the CLI-only id column is the sole place ids surface outside `status.json`. Errors funnel through `error.rs`'s taxonomy (`BadImpact`, `BadDifficulty`, `StoreCorrupt`, `StoreNotEmpty`, `TaskIdNotFound`, `Io`) and no code path panics on user input.